 that we read the trope of Nahdah as Walter Benjamin might have, as "one of the monuments of the bourgeoisie that [are] already in ruins." Financial speculation engendered an anxious mixture of hope and fear formally expressed in the mingling of financial news and serialized novels in such Arabic journals as Al-Jinān, Al-Muqtataf, and Al-Hilāl. Holt recasts the historiography of the Nahdah, showing its sense of rise and renaissance to be a utopian, imperially mediated narrative of capital that encrypted its inevitable counterpart, capital flight.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aArabic fictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature publishingxEconomic aspectszEgyptxHistoryy19th century. 0aLiterature publishingxEconomic aspectszLebanonxHistoryy19th century. 0aSerialized fictionzEgyptxHistory and criticism. 0aSerialized fictionzLebanonxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Middle Eastern.2bisacsh  aArabic Novel.  aBeirut.  aCairo.  aJurjī Zaydān.  aKhalīl al-Khūrī.  aNahdah.  aSalīm al-Bustānī.  aYaʿqūb Ṣarrūf.  acapitalism.  acotton.  asilk.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311072901640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823276059zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823276059423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823276059.jpg  a978-3-11-072901-6  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK